      dramaticSignificance: `Act Two is the structural heart of the play, containing the longest and most complex revelations. Gerald's confession provides an emotional centre — his relationship with Daisy was the most nuanced and arguably the most exploitative of the connections revealed, because it involved genuine affection mixed with the inherent power imbalance of a wealthy man keeping a working-class woman as his mistress.

The act's most powerful dramatic technique is the sustained dramatic irony of Mrs Birling's self-condemnation. Priestley builds this slowly and deliberately, allowing Mrs Birling to dig herself deeper and deeper into a moral position that will become untenable once Eric's involvement is revealed. The audience watches with growing horror as Mrs Birling insists that the father bears sole responsibility — and the tension of knowing what she does not know creates some of the most effective dramatic moments in twentieth-century British theatre.

Mrs Birling's interrogation also reveals the play's most damning indictment of the class system: a charity designed to help the most vulnerable members of society is run by the very people whose prejudices prevent them from offering genuine help. The system is not merely failing — it is actively designed to exclude and punish those it claims to serve.

The act also deepens the generational divide: Sheila's desperate attempts to stop her mother from condemning Eric show that the younger generation can see the moral catastrophe approaching, while the older generation remains wilfully blind.`,
      stageDirectionsAnalysis: `Priestley's directions for Mrs Birling emphasise her "social superiority" and her attempts to maintain control through bearing and manner rather than argument. She is described as speaking with cold authority, and her physical stiffness contrasts with Sheila's increasing emotional openness. This physical language reinforces the play's thematic concern with rigidity versus flexibility, closed-mindedness versus the capacity for change.

Gerald is described as showing genuine distress during his confession, which complicates the audience's response to him. He is not a simple villain but a man who is genuinely moved by the memory of Daisy Renton. His departure — going for a walk to collect himself — is physically significant: he leaves the enclosed space of the Birling home, which by this point has become a moral courtroom.

The most powerful stage direction of the act is the final one: "Eric enters, looking pale and distressed," and Mrs Birling, "with a cry," realises the truth. The physical description of Eric — pale, distressed — mirrors Eva Smith's suffering, creating a visual link between the exploiter and the exploited. Mrs Birling's cry is the sound of her moral framework collapsing, though she will attempt to rebuild it in Act Three.

The continuous real-time setting (the entire play takes place in one evening in one room) intensifies the claustrophobic tension of this act. There is no escape from the Inspector's questioning, and the characters — particularly Mrs Birling — are trapped both physically and morally.`,
