          speaker: 'Inspector Goole',
          analysis: 'This is the climactic speech of the play and the fullest expression of Priestley\'s socialist message. The phrase "members of one body" is both a political statement and a quasi-religious one, echoing St Paul\'s teaching that all Christians are part of the body of Christ. Priestley, though not conventionally religious, understood the power of biblical language to convey moral urgency. The warning of "fire and blood and anguish" is a prophetic reference to the World Wars that the 1945 audience had just lived through. Priestley is arguing that the selfish individualism represented by Birling — the refusal to accept responsibility for others — was the moral failure that led to global catastrophe. The speech functions as both a warning and a call to action: the audience must choose social responsibility or face the consequences.',
