      howPriestleyUsesThem: `Priestley uses the Inspector as his dramatic and ideological centrepiece. The Inspector is not a fully realised psychological character but a theatrical device — a moral force that exposes truth and demands accountability. His mysterious nature (who is he really?) serves Priestley's purpose because it prevents the audience from dismissing his message as the opinion of one man. If the Inspector is supernatural, his message carries cosmic authority. If he is a fraud, then the truth he uncovered is no less true for having been revealed by illegitimate means. Either way, the moral argument stands.

The Inspector also represents an egalitarian challenge to the class system. He treats everyone with the same directness, refusing to defer to wealth or social position. In the Birling dining room — a space of privilege and hierarchy — the Inspector creates a temporary democracy of accountability where everyone is equally subject to moral scrutiny.

Priestley uses the Inspector to model the kind of society he wanted to build: one where every person is held responsible for their impact on others, regardless of class, wealth, or social standing.`,
