      howPriestleyUsesThem: `Priestley uses Gerald to complicate the play's moral scheme. Gerald is not straightforwardly villainous — his relationship with Daisy involved genuine kindness, and his honest confession shows integrity. But Priestley shows that kindness within an unjust system is not sufficient: Gerald helped one woman temporarily while doing nothing to challenge the system that made her vulnerable.

Gerald also serves as a warning about the seductive power of intelligence and charm. He is the character who dismantles the Inspector's credibility, using his analytical skills to find factual inconsistencies. But Priestley shows that Gerald's intelligence serves moral evasion rather than moral growth — he uses his skills to construct an escape route from accountability rather than to deepen his understanding of responsibility.

Gerald represents the moderate, well-meaning member of the upper class who is willing to help individuals but unwilling to change structures. Priestley suggests that this kind of genteel benevolence is ultimately as harmful as Birling's overt selfishness, because it maintains the illusion that the system works while doing nothing to reform it.`,
