      howPriestleyUsesThem: `Eva Smith is Priestley's most powerful dramatic creation precisely because she never appears on stage. Her absence forces the audience to construct her from the testimonies of those who exploited her — and this act of imaginative construction is itself a form of moral engagement. The audience must work to see Eva as a person, just as the Birlings must (and mostly fail to) work to see her as a person.

Eva represents every victim of the class system — the millions of working-class men and women whose lives are shaped and often destroyed by the decisions of the powerful. Her name (Eva = Eve, Smith = everyman) reinforces this symbolic function. Priestley uses her to show that the victims of social injustice are not abstractions or statistics but real people with feelings, hopes, and moral integrity.

Eva's moral superiority over every character in the play is Priestley's most radical argument: the working class are not merely equal to the upper class — in terms of moral worth, they are often superior. This reversal of the class hierarchy's implicit moral assumptions is at the heart of Priestley's socialism.`,
