      name: 'Edna',
      role: 'The Birlings\' maid',
      arc: `Edna is a minor character with a major symbolic function. She is the Birlings' maid — a working-class woman who exists on the margins of the family's awareness, serving their needs while remaining almost invisible to them. She has very few lines, but her presence throughout the play serves as a constant, silent reminder of the class system that the Inspector is exposing.

Edna is the one who answers the door to the Inspector and announces his arrival. This is dramatically significant: a working-class woman admits the moral reckoning into the Birling household. Edna's quiet, unobtrusive presence during the family's celebrations and subsequent interrogation mirrors Eva Smith's position in society — present, necessary, but unacknowledged.

Priestley uses Edna to ensure that the audience cannot forget, even for a moment, that the Birlings' comfortable existence depends on the labour of people they barely notice. While they argue about their responsibility toward Eva Smith, a living working-class woman is serving them dinner and clearing their plates. The irony is pointed and deliberate.`,
