          quote: 'If men will not learn that lesson, then they will be taught it in fire and blood and anguish.',
          analysis: 'The Inspector\'s apocalyptic warning connects personal morality to political catastrophe. The "fire and blood and anguish" is a reference to the World Wars, which Priestley presents as the inevitable consequence of a society that refuses to acknowledge collective responsibility. This elevates the play\'s moral argument from the personal to the historical, insisting that individual selfishness has global consequences.',
