      analysis: `Birling's self-justification is stated as absolute fact rather than opinion. He does not engage with the moral argument — he simply asserts that he was right and expects that to end the discussion. This certainty in his own rightness is what makes Birling impervious to the Inspector's moral message and what Priestley presents as the most dangerous characteristic of the ruling class.

The word "quite" adds an air of casual, unexamined confidence. Birling treats the moral question of Eva's dismissal as settled — as obvious and unremarkable. Priestley shows that this kind of moral complacency is more dangerous than deliberate cruelty because it prevents even the possibility of self-examination.`,
      grade9Interpretation: 'A grade 9 response would connect Birling\'s self-justification to the concept of moral certainty as a barrier to growth. The student might argue that Priestley presents absolute self-assurance as the enemy of moral progress — those who are certain they are right cannot learn, and those who cannot learn are doomed to repeat their mistakes. This connects to the play\'s cyclical ending: the Birlings who feel justified are the ones who will face the second investigation, trapped in a loop of their own making.',
