  comparisonNotes: [
    {
      text: 'A Christmas Carol by Charles Dickens',
      connections: `Both texts present a wealthy, selfish protagonist who is visited by a supernatural figure and forced to confront the consequences of their actions on the poor. Scrooge, like Birling, represents capitalist individualism and is shown the human cost of his philosophy. Both texts argue for social responsibility and collective care.

Key differences: Scrooge is redeemed and changes, while Birling refuses to learn. Priestley is more pessimistic about the older generation's capacity for change — his hope lies with the young, while Dickens believes even the most hardened individual can be transformed.

Both texts use supernatural or ambiguous figures (the Ghosts/the Inspector) to deliver their moral message, suggesting that the truth about social responsibility cannot be communicated through normal channels — it requires an extraordinary intervention.`,
    },
    {
      text: 'Macbeth by William Shakespeare',
      connections: `Both texts explore the corrupting effects of power and the consequences of immoral actions. Both feature characters who attempt to escape the consequences of their actions and find that they cannot. Lady Macbeth's sleepwalking ("Out, damned spot") echoes the way guilt pursues the Birlings even when they try to dismiss it.

Both plays use ambiguous supernatural elements (the witches/the Inspector) to drive the action, and both raise questions about fate versus free will — were the characters destined to act as they did, or did they have a choice?

Key difference: Macbeth is about individual ambition, while An Inspector Calls is about collective responsibility. Priestley's argument is systemic rather than personal.`,
    },
    {
      text: 'The Strange Case of Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde by R.L. Stevenson',
      connections: `Both texts explore the gap between public respectability and private morality. The Birlings, like Jekyll's circle of respectable gentlemen, maintain a veneer of propriety that conceals darker truths. Both texts suggest that Victorian/Edwardian respectability is a performance that hides rather than reflects moral reality.

Both texts also explore class: Hyde is associated with the lower-class areas of London, just as Eva Smith is relegated to the margins of society. Both texts show the wealthy exploiting or destroying the vulnerable while maintaining their social reputation.`,
    },
    {
      text: 'Romeo and Juliet by William Shakespeare',
      connections: `Both texts explore the consequences of social divisions — class in An Inspector Calls, family in Romeo and Juliet. Both argue that artificial barriers between groups of people lead to tragedy. Both feature younger generations who are more morally aware than their parents but are unable to change the system that constrains them.

Both texts end without clear resolution — the question of whether the feuding families or the Birling household will genuinely change is left open.`,
    },
    {
      text: 'Power and Conflict Poetry (AQA)',
      connections: `Several poems in the Power and Conflict anthology connect to themes in An Inspector Calls:

"London" by William Blake: Both texts critique a society that ignores the suffering of the poor. Blake's "marks of weakness, marks of woe" parallel Eva's suffering at the hands of the powerful.

"Ozymandias" by Percy Bysshe Shelley: Both texts explore the hubris of the powerful. Birling's confidence in his own authority echoes Ozymandias's arrogance, and both are ultimately revealed as hollow.

"Checking Out Me History" by John Agard: Both texts challenge dominant narratives and insist on hearing the voices of those who have been silenced by power structures.

"My Last Duchess" by Robert Browning: Both texts feature powerful men who treat women as objects to be controlled. The Duke's treatment of his Duchess parallels Gerald's and Eric's treatment of Eva — in both cases, male power over women is absolute and unquestioned.`,
    },
  ],

