  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // MINI ESSAY: THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE TITLE
  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  titleAnalysis: {
    title: 'An Inspector Calls',
    analysis: `The title "An Inspector Calls" is deceptively simple but carries multiple layers of meaning that deepen as the play progresses.

On the surface, it is a straightforward description of the plot: a police inspector arrives at the Birling household to investigate a death. This places the play in the genre of the detective story or mystery thriller — a familiar, popular form that would have attracted a wide audience in 1945.

However, the indefinite article "An" is significant. It is not "The Inspector Calls" (suggesting a specific, known individual) but "An Inspector Calls" (suggesting one of many possible inspectors). This choice hints at the play's central ambiguity: who is the Inspector? The indefinite article suggests he could be anyone — a police officer, a supernatural figure, a collective conscience, a representative of the working class. He is not a definitive, identifiable individual but a type, a function, a role that could be filled by anyone with the moral conviction to challenge the powerful.

The verb "Calls" has a double meaning in English. It can mean "visits" (an inspector pays a call on the Birlings), but it can also mean "summons" or "demands" (as in "duty calls"). The second meaning suggests that the Inspector's visit is not optional but inevitable — the Birlings have been summoned to account for their actions, and they cannot refuse the call. This connects to the play's argument that moral accountability is inescapable: you can postpone it, but it will eventually find you.

The title also foreshadows the play's cyclical structure. "An Inspector Calls" describes not just one visit but a type of event — an event that can repeat. When the final phone call announces that a new inspector is on his way, the title takes on a new meaning: this is not a one-time event but a recurring phenomenon. An inspector will always call, sooner or later, because the consequences of moral failure cannot be permanently suppressed.

Finally, the title can be read as Priestley's description of his own play. The play itself is "an inspector" — it inspects its audience, examining their beliefs about class, responsibility, and morality, and challenging them to change. Priestley designed the play to do to its audience what the Inspector does to the Birlings: to strip away comfortable illusions and force a confrontation with moral truth. In this sense, every performance of An Inspector Calls is literally an inspector calling on the audience.`,
  },

  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // WHAT MAKES THIS PLAY A MASTERPIECE — CLOSING ANALYSIS
  // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  closingAnalysis: {
    title: 'Why An Inspector Calls Endures',
    analysis: `An Inspector Calls has remained one of the most studied and most frequently performed plays in the English language for over eighty years. Its endurance is not simply due to its inclusion on GCSE syllabuses but to its extraordinary dramatic effectiveness and the continuing relevance of its message.

The play's formal perfection is one reason for its lasting power. Priestley constructs a dramatic machine of remarkable precision — every element serves a purpose, every line contributes to the argument, and the structure creates an irresistible momentum that carries the audience from comfortable celebration to moral crisis in a single, unbroken evening. The play wastes nothing. Even the most casual-seeming lines — Birling's praise of the cook, Eric's awkward interruptions, Mrs Birling's social corrections — turn out to be clues that foreshadow later revelations.

The play's political argument has not lost its force because the issues it addresses have not been resolved. Income inequality, the exploitation of workers, the sexual vulnerability of women, the use of institutional power to protect the privileged, and the refusal of the powerful to accept responsibility for the consequences of their actions — all of these remain urgent social problems. The Inspector's message that "we are responsible for each other" continues to challenge societies that prioritise individual wealth over collective welfare.

The play's emotional power comes from its characters — not as realistic psychological portraits (they are too schematic for that) but as moral archetypes that audiences recognise in themselves and in the people around them. We have all known Birlings: confident, successful, and utterly certain of their own rightness. We have all known Mrs Birlings: cold, prejudiced, and immune to appeal. We have known Sheilas: people who, confronted with the truth about themselves, find the courage to change. And we have known Geralds: clever enough to understand but unwilling to act on their understanding.

The play's final question — will you learn the lesson, or will you need to be taught it in fire and blood and anguish? — remains the question that every generation must answer for itself. Priestley wrote the play for the generation of 1945. But every new audience inherits the question, and the play's cyclical structure ensures that it never stops asking.

An Inspector Calls is not merely a play about 1912 or about 1945. It is a play about the permanent human struggle between selfishness and solidarity, between the desire for comfortable ignorance and the demand for moral truth. It will endure for as long as that struggle continues — which is to say, for as long as there are human beings capable of both exploitation and compassion.

The play's genius lies in its simplicity. Priestley does not need elaborate staging, special effects, or a large cast to make his argument. He needs only a dining room, a family, and a stranger who asks uncomfortable questions. This simplicity is the source of the play's universality — any audience, in any country, in any era, can understand the moral challenge that the Inspector presents. The Birlings' dining room is every room where the comfortable refuse to see the consequences of their comfort. The Inspector is every voice that insists on truth in the face of denial. And Eva Smith is every person whose suffering is ignored because the powerful find it inconvenient to acknowledge.

Priestley's final gift to the audience is the play's open ending. By refusing to tell us what happens next, he hands the moral question to us. The Inspector has called. The truth has been revealed. The consequences are approaching. The only question remaining is: what will we do about it?`,
  },
